definition.value: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the beta subunit of the catenin complex.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with microtubules, filaments composed of tubulin monomers.

Combining with incidental electromagnetic radiation, particularly visible light, and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein -  promotes the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha subunit of a heterotrimeric G-protein complex.

A secretory organelle, some 50 nm in diameter, of presynaptic nerve terminals -  accumulates in high concentrations of neurotransmitters and secretes these into the synaptic cleft by fusion with the 'active zone' of the presynaptic plasma membrane.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a protein C-terminus, the end of any peptide chain at which the 1-carboxy function of a constituent amino acid is not attached in peptide linkage to another amino-acid residue.

Any protein complex that interacts with RNA polymerase II to increase (positive transcription elongation factor) or reduce (negative transcription elongation factor) the rate of transcription elongation.

label.value: positive transcription elongation factor complex b

definition.value: A transcription elongation factor complex that facilitates the transition from abortive to productive elongation by phosphorylating the CTD domain of the large subunit of DNA-directed RNA polymerase II, holoenzyme. Contains cyclin T and a cyclin-dependent protein kinase catalytic subunit.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to drive the unwinding of a DNA or RNA helix.
Catalysis of the transfer of monocarboxylic acids from one side of the membrane to the other. A monocarboxylic acid is an organic acid with one COOH group.
Combining with a pentraxin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with a neuronal pentraxin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
The action characteristic of eclosion hormone, a peptide hormone that, upon receptor binding, triggers the death of certain muscles and neurons during insect metamorphosis.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with high-density lipoprotein particle, a lipoprotein particle with a high density (typically 1.063-1.21 g|ml) and a diameter of 5-10 nm that contains APOAs and may contain APOCs and APOE.
Combining with a diuretic hormone and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity.
A ferritin complex located in the cell. Intracellular ferritin complexes contain 24 subunits, in a mixture of L (light) chains and H (heavy) chains.
Combining with an extracellular messenger and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to results in a change in cellular activity involved in axon guidance.
Increases the activity of an enzyme.

label.value: calcium sensitive guanylate cyclase activator activity

definition.value: Increases the activity of guanylate cyclase in response to a change in calcium ion concentration.
Increases the rate of GTP hydrolysis by the GTPase ARF.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with chitin, a linear polysaccharide consisting of beta-(1--gt-4)-linked N-acetyl-D-glucosamine residues.
Combining with glutamate and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of a chloride ion by a channel that opens when extracellular glutamate has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.
The stopping, prevention or reduction of the activity of the enzyme ornithine decarboxylase.
Complex that possesses guanylate cyclase activity and is not bound to a membrane.
A protein complex that forms a transmembrane channel through which potassium ions may cross a cell membrane in response to changes in membrane potential.
Functions in the termination of translation.
Catalysis of the transfer of an acetyl group to a nitrogen atom on the acceptor molecule.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of a phosphodiester to give a phosphomonoester and a free hydroxyl group.
The function that stimulates a cell to grow or proliferate. Most growth factors have other actions besides the induction of cell growth or proliferation.

label.value: imaginal disc growth factor receptor binding

definition.value: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an imaginal disc growth factor receptor.

Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of a calcium ion by a voltage-gated channel that is activated in response to light. A voltage-gated channel is a channel whose open state is dependent on the voltage across the membrane in which it is embedded.
A protein complex that forms a transmembrane channel through which calcium ions may cross a cell membrane in response to changes in membrane potential generated in response to a light stimulus.

Membrane associated dimeric protein (240 and 220 kDa) of erythrocytes. Forms a complex with ankyrin, actin and probably other components of the membrane cytoskeleton, so that there is a mesh of proteins underlying the plasma membrane, potentially restricting the lateral mobility of integral proteins.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any protein component of any cytoskeleton (actin, microtubule, or intermediate filament cytoskeleton).
The binding activity of a molecule that brings together a cytoskeletal protein and one or more other molecules, permitting them to function in a coordinated way.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate -  this reaction requires the presence of single- or double-stranded DNA, and it drives another reaction.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of the epoxide in a juvenile hormone to the corresponding diol.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with 5S ribosomal RNA, the smallest RNA constituent of a ribosome.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the unprocessed 5S ribosomal RNA transcript.
Catalysis of the reaction -  an alcohol + NADP+ -eq- an aldehyde + NADPH + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-L-fucose + beta-D-galactosyl-R -eq- GDP + alpha-L-fucosyl-(1,2)-beta-D-galactosyl-R.
Catalysis of the reaction -  alpha-D-galactose 1-phosphate + UDP-D-glucose -eq- alpha-D-glucose 1-phosphate + UDP-D-galactose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine + beta-D-galactosyl-1,4-N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-R -eq- UDP + N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-1,6-beta-D-galactosyl-1,4-N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-R.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2-oxoglutarate + L-histidine -eq- 3-(imidazol-5-yl)pyruvate + L-glutamate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (2S)-2-methylacyl-CoA -eq- (2R)-2-methylacyl-CoA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine(1+) + nicotinamide -eq- 1-methylnicotinamide + S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.

Catalysis of the reactions -  peptide-L-methionine + thioredoxin disulfide + H2O -eq- peptide-L-methionine (S)-S-oxide + thioredoxin, and L-methionine + thioredoxin disulfide + H2O -eq- L-methionine (S)-S-oxide + thioredoxin. Can act on oxidized methionine in peptide linkage with specificity for the S enantiomer. Thioredoxin disulfide is the oxidized form of thioredoxin.
Catalysis of the reaction -  6-phospho-D-gluconate + NADP+ -eq- 6-phospho-2-dehydro-D-gluconate + NADPH.
Catalysis of the reaction -  H(2)O + O(2) + sarcosine -eq- formaldehyde + glycine + H(2)O(2).
Catalysis of the reaction -  prostaglandin H(2) -eq- prostaglandin I(2).
